inations in Mahabaleshwar, attracting many pilgrims. It is commonly referred to as the Mahabali. Throughout the year, tourists and followers throng the temple to enjoy peace and tranquilly. The temple is beautifully constructed; it has stone walls and is separated into two sections that are centre hall and the sanctum sanctorum. This temple is split between the sanctum sanctorum and the central hall by a five-foot-high stone wall. The mythology surrounding the Mahabaleshwar temple is many as well. According to one tradition, Maratha king Shri Shivaji Maharaj weighed his mother Jijabai in gold in this temple before donating the riches to charity. Lord Shiva's Trishul, Rudraksha, Damru, and a bed almost 300 years old are also kept at this shrine. The original Hemadant architectural design of South India is typified by the Mahabaleshwar Temple. The 6-foot-long Shiva lingam is a major and most prominent feature of the temple, of which only the top is visible. This lingam displays Lord Shiva's stone manifestation. The Mahabaleshwar Temple has a relaxed and tranquil ambience. Tourists to the temple come from all over the world to experience Lord Shiva's serene atmosphere. Timing: 6:00 am to 7:00 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 8. Panchgani Panchgani is a prominent hill resort in the Indian state of Maharashtra and is named after the five gorgeous hills surrounding it. This hill town is located at an elevation of around 1334 meters above sea level. It is surrounded by imposing mountains, bleak valleys, flowing waterfalls, and dense forests. This village, which is covered by the Sahyadri mountains, was once a lovely summer hideaway for British officials. Many visitors are currently attracted to Panchgani by its tranquillity, natural beauty, and adventure. The notable attractions in Panchgani are Sydney Point, Table Land, Rajpuri Caves, and Dhom Dam, further enhancing the area's beauty and attractiveness. Panchgani offers its tourists a broad range of mind-boggling activities. T