ent, Wax Museum, Mapro Garden, Dhobi Waterfall, Venna Lake, Helen's Point, Table Land, and Rajapuri Caves. Below, Mahabaleshwar's best tourist places are described. 1. Elephant's Head Point Elephant's Head Point in Mahabaleshwar, also known as Needle Hole Point, offers breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape. Needle's point is the best place to visit during sundown. It is one of the greatest sites to visit in Mahabaleshwar, The rock present here has been compared to the head of an elephant, and the gap between the elephant's trunk and foot has the appearance of a hole-like needle. The greatest time to visit Mahabaleshwar is during the monsoon when everything blooms. Elephant's Head Point is a greenery area during the rainy season. Visitors can take public transportation to reach this location to enjoy beautiful views of waterfalls rushing out of the Sahyadri Mountain range and posing for wonderful photos. Elephant's Head Point is well-known for its beautiful views of the Sahyadri mountains. You could even find yourself in a cloudy area if you're fortunate. The best time to visit this location is early morning to enjoy the magnificent view, but if you arrive late, make sure not to miss the sun setting behind Sahyadri Mountain. Tourists can see a panoramic image of Pratapgarh fort, which is encircled by the Kova valley on one side and the Savitri valley on the other. Address: 402303 Satara, Maharashtra Timing: Timings are from 6 am to 7 pm Entry fee: Free 2. Chinaman's Falls One of the most well-known attractions to visit in Mahabaleshwar is the Chinaman's Falls, which is about 2.5 km south of the city in the Koyana valley. Since the Chinese were responsible for maintaining the surrounding gardens, therefore waterfall is known as Chinaman's waterfall. As sunlight passes through the falls, that time the water shimmers like gold and diamonds. The beautiful surroundings, stunning waterfalls, and gardens make it a perfect vacation destination. It is the ideal destination for a holiday that offers a stunning experience. Arrange a picnic at Chinaman's falls for you and your loved ones. The monsoon season is the best time to view the falls. It is one of the favourite areas to visit in Mahabaleshwar because of its peaceful surroundings. If you visit Mahabaleshwar, you should visit Chinaman Falls. The time requires to visit and see Chinaman's falls is 2 or 3 hours. Address: 412806 Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra Timing: All day Entry fee: Entry is free 3. Dhobi Waterfall It is one of Mahabaleshwar's best tourist destinations. Dhobi falls are a collection of waterfalls that connect Elphinston Point and Lodwick, and after that, connect Petit Road to Old Mahabaleshwar Road. The Dhobi waterfall is located around 3 kilometres from Mahabaleshwar's main town. For adventure lovers and picnickers, a waterfall has always been a particularly attractive destination. One of the greatest spots to visit in Mahabaleshwar is the Koyna River; it is a tributary of the Krishna River that falls directly into the valley from the mountains. Visitors can spend the day in this place that is encircled by the waterfall, greenery, rocks and natural beauty to avoid dullness. Therefore, a trip to the Dhobi waterfall should be top of the list of things to do in Mahabaleshwar. The picnic area at Dhobi waterfalls is very wonderful. The monsoon season is the best time to travel there. Timing: 6 am to 6 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 4. Arthur's Seat The Arthur's Seat is one of Mahabaleshwar's most well-known tourist attractions. It is also known as the Madhi Mahaal or the Queen of the Points. Arthur's Seat is around 13 kilometres from Mahabaleshwar's market. The unique feature of this location is that if you toss a light object down the valley, it will quickly rise due to air pressure. The Konkan and the Deccan are seen on one side of Arthur's Seat and surrounded by an amazing view. October to June is the ideal time to visit Arthur's Seat. The climate here is generally pleasant; in summer, it is mild, and in winter, it is chilly. Suicide Point is another name for this area. There are six viewpoints at Arthur's Seat Point. They are as follows Tiger Sprint Point, Arthur's Seat Point, Malcolm Point, Window Point, Echo Point and Hunter Point are the six Arthurs seats. Address: 412806 Satara, Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra Timing: 9:00 am to 8:00 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 5. Venna Lake The Venna Lake is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Mahabaleshwar that visitors should not miss. It is an artificial lake that Shri Appasaheb Maharaj, a descendant of Shivaji Maharaj, constructed in 1942. The 7 km to 8 km long Veena Lake is surrounded by lush forest, enhancing its attractiveness. Pratap Singh Garden is situated on the banks of this lake, which is a popular tourist attraction. To fulfil the water needs of the city of Mahabaleshwar, it was initially constructed. At Venna Lake, there are many enjoyable activities that one can participate in. The visitor enjoys sailing in the row and paddle boats with their family and friends. There are rides for kids also, like the merry-go-round and the toy train, in addition to horseback riding. To satisfy your hunger around the lake, there are many restaurants well famous for their street food like corn. Mulberries, strawberries, and carrots, as well as bhelpuri, are examples of fresh fruits. Address: 412806 Satara, Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra. Timing: 8 am to 8 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 6. Wilson Point (Sunrise Point) One of the greatest spots to visit in Mahabaleshwar is Wilson point, commonly referred to as the Sunrise point, since it is the highest point in the city. Watch the sunrise from Wilson Point while standing tall at 4,710 feet above sea level and mesmerize yourself. The sun rising brightens your day and gives you energy for the trip ahead. Sir Leslie Wilson, the Governor of Bombay during the British administration, is honoured by having his name given to the spot. Three watchtowers at this sunrise position allow visitors to view Mahabaleshwar's stunning natural splendour. Address: 412806 Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra Timing: 7:00 am to 6:00 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 7. Mahabaleshwar Temple Lord Shiva is honoured in the Mahabaleshwar Temple, which is situated 6 km north of the main city. It was constructed in the 16th century. It is one of the most well-known tourist destinations in Mahabaleshwar, attracting many pilgrims. It is commonly referred to as the Mahabali. Throughout the year, tourists and followers throng the temple to enjoy peace and tranquilly. The temple is beautifully constructed; it has stone walls and is separated into two sections that are centre hall and the sanctum sanctorum. This temple is split between the sanctum sanctorum and the central hall by a five-foot-high stone wall. The mythology surrounding the Mahabaleshwar temple is many as well. According to one tradition, Maratha king Shri Shivaji Maharaj weighed his mother Jijabai in gold in this temple before donating the riches to charity. Lord Shiva's Trishul, Rudraksha, Damru, and a bed almost 300 years old are also kept at this shrine. The original Hemadant architectural design of South India is typified by the Mahabaleshwar Temple. The 6-foot-long Shiva lingam is a major and most prominent feature of the temple, of which only the top is visible. This lingam displays Lord Shiva's stone manifestation. The Mahabaleshwar Temple has a relaxed and tranquil ambience. Tourists to the temple come from all over the world to experience Lord Shiva's serene atmosphere. Timing: 6:00 am to 7:00 pm Entry fee: Entry is free 8. Panchgani Panchgani is a prominent hill resort in the Indian state of Maharashtra and is named after the five gorgeous hills surrounding it. This hill town is located at an elevation of around 1334 meters above sea level. It is surrounded by imposing mountains, bleak valleys, flowing waterfalls, and dense forests. This village, which is covered by the Sahyadri